As an introverted creative entrepreneur who values their privacy, running a business shouldn't feel so awkward, but sometimes it does. Most online resources and mentors tell you to interact with large (evil) tech companies in an extroverted way, to follow the algorithm, and to share your personal charm by putting up ads. On that service, you have to get verified, stay online 24/7, answer questions with your own video, and respond immediately. Video, video, and more video.
One-third.
For me, this year is a year of transformation.
I don't want to dedicate my money, data and energy to large tech companies anymore, nor do I want to hear the opinions of coaches who will only apply single, extroverted solutions to every individual. I'm exploring new business models, and I'm also working to overcome my long-held notion that success can only be achieved by doing things in a certain way.
Wish me good luck!
The first step has been taken.
I deleted my Meta and Pinterest trackers from my website and quit Facebook, and also deleted my personal WhatsApp account.
Yesterday, I finally removed the last external tracker from my website, Google Analytics, and I feel fantastic.
To better support GDPR, I have recently subscribed to a European CRM service and will be migrating my business to it over the next few weeks.
I've moved my MX records to Proton now, and I have full SPF, DKIM and DMARC without having to pay Google to do basic email verification.
Three in a row.
